The {\versecalc} grammar can be a bit unwieldy, with explicit |defKW| and ANF-like restrictions allowing only values, not arbitrary expressions, in in array literals and function-applications. To keep the examples readable, we allow ourselves a bit of syntactic sugar, summarized in \cref{fig:sugar}:
\begin{itemize}
\item With |:=| we simulatenous introduce and assign a variable.
\item When defining functions, we allow simple patterns on the left of |:=|
\item When writing expressions that are not values in function application and pairs, we omit assigning them to a variable first.
\item We allow the use of |for| and |if| as explained above.
\end{itemize}

