\subsection{List functions}

We can define the typical list functions one would expect from functional programming
by using the duality between arrays and choices, as seen in \cref{fig:list-functions}.
An array can be turned into choices by indexing, |applyx a i|, with a logical variable |i|.
Conversely, choices can be turned into an array using |allKW|.
The choice operator, |choice|, serves as both |cons| and |append| for choices
and |oneKW| is like |head| for choices.

To obtain the first element of an array, we turn the array into a sequence of choices and then pick out the first value using |oneKW|. If the array is empty, |head| fails.

To get the tail of an array, again we apply the array to a fresh variable, and restrict that variable with |i > 0|. This way, the expresison fails a tthe first value and only the other values are collected by |allKW|. This definition of |tail| returns the empty array if |xs| is empty or not even an array.

We can implement |applyx cons (x,xs)| by collecing with |allKW| the choices we get from choosing |x|, or all the elements of |xs|, and similarly we can define |append|.

For the function |map|, which applies a function to each element of an array and collects the results, two possible implementation come to mind, and they differ when the function passed to |map|  fails or produces more than a single value. The definition |mapFlat(f,xs) := all (def i (applyx f (applyx xs i)))| would flatten the choices from iterating through |xs| with the choices taken by |f|, so |mapFlat((lam x ((x, x+1))), (10,20))| $\equiv$ |(10,11,20,21)|.

But often this is not what we want; and we want the effects of |f|, such as failure or returning multiple values, to affect the whole expression and obtain the cartesian product of these choices. The expression
|map((lam x ((x, x+1))), (10,20))| should reduce to |(10,20)`choice`(10,21) `choice` (11,20) `choice` (11,21)|.
We get that behaviour if we simly define |map| much like in any other functional programming language: If the array is empty, return it, else apply |f| to the |head|, recurse on the |tail| and assemble the result with |cons|.\label{sec:map}

How can we filter an array with a predicate |p|? We turn the array into the sequence of choices, and let those fail where |p| fails before collecting the other values into an array.

If we use |oneKW| instead of |allKW|, we get the function that checks if |p| holds for some element of the array, and returns the first matching element, or fails if |p| does not hold for any element.

And to test if a predicate |p| holds for every element of an array |xs|, we can simply use |map(p,xs)|! If |p| fails for any value, the whole call to |map(p,xs)| fails.


\subsection{Comprehensions with |for|} \label{sec:for}

Source languages can use this to build more featureful constructs like |for|, mimicking the list comprehension in languages like Haskell or Python:
The expression |for^(e_1) in e_2| will evaluate |e_2| for each of the choices in |e_1|.
The |e_1| is called the {\em domain} of the loop.


The scoping is peculiar that variables bound in |e_1| also scope over |e_2|.
So, e.g., |for^(def x (x = 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5)) in (x+1)| will reduce to the array |(3,4,6)|.
This example can, with the |:=| shorthand, be written |for^(x := 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5) in (x+1)|.

Like list comprehension it supports filtering, but in Verse this falls out naturally by just using
a possibly failing expression in the domain.
So, |for^(x := 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5; x > 2) in (x+1)| reduces to the array |(4,6)|.

Nested iteration in a |for| works as expected, and requires nothing special.
So, |for^(x:=10 `choice` 20; y := 1 `choice` 2 `choice` 3) in x+y| reduces to |(11, 12, 13, 21, 22, 23)|

Just like |if| is defined in terms of the primitive |oneKW| we can define |for|
in terms of the primitive |all e|.
Again, we have to be careful when |e_2| itself fails or produces multiple results;
simply writing |all (e1;e2)| would give the wrong semantics. So we put |e_2| under a lambda, and
apply each element of the array to |()| afterwards, using the |map| function defined above. The full desugaring for |for^(e_1) in e_2| is thus
\[
|applyx map ((lam z (applyx z ())), all (e_1; lam x e_2))|.
\]

Note how this achieves that peculiar scoping rule: variables defined in |e_1| are in scope in |e_2|.
Any effects (like being multivalued) in |e_2| will not affect the choices defined by |e_1| since they are in a thunk.
So, e.g., |for^(x:=1 `choice` 2) in {3 `choice` x}| will reduce to |(3, 3) `choice` (1, 3) `choice` (3, 2) `choice` (1, 2)|.
At this point it is crucial to use |map|, not |mapFlat|.

Given that array indexing expands into choices, we can iterate over array indices and elements using |for|.
E.g., |for^(def (i, x) (x = applyx a i)) in x+i| will produce an array with the elements of |a|, increased by their index in |a|.


\subsection{Enumerations}
Making a choice between a sequence of numbers can be expressed like this
$$
\begin{array}{lll}
  |fromTo^(lo,hi)| & := & |if lo > hi then fail else lo `choice` applyx fromTo (lo+1,hi)|
\end{array}
$$
so |for^(x:= applyx fromTo (1,5)) in x| will reduce to the array |(1,2,3,4,5)|.

\subsection{Handling out-of-bounds errors}
Indexing out-of-bounds of an array results in |fail|.
This means that we cannot avoid handling this case.
$$
|if x:=a^(5) then print^(x) else print^("out of bounds")|
$$

