\section{Rewrite rules} \label{sec:rewrite-rules}

\input{rewrites}

How can we give a precise semantics to a non-strict functional
programming language?  Here are some possiblities:
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{High level.} A denotational semantics is the classical approach, but it is quite mathematical
  (and hence not a good way to explain to programmer what their program means),
  and it cannot distinguish between call-by-need and call-by-name (hence ``high level'').
\item \emph{Low level.} A big-step operational semantics typically involves explaining how a (heap,expression) starting point evaluates to a (heap,value) pair; Launchbury's natural semantics for lazy evaluation \cite{launchbury:natural} is the classic paper.  The heap, threaded through the semantics, accounts for updating thunks as they are evaluated.
\item \emph{Lower level}. Despite its ``operational semantics'' title, this big step approach
  does not convey accurate operational intutition, because it goes all the way to a value
  in one step. So-called ``small-step'' operational semantics are therefore widely used;
  they typically describe how a (heap, expression, stack) configuration evolves, one small
  step at a time \cite{pj:stg-machine}.
  The difficulty is that the description is now so low-level that it is again hard to explain to programmers.
\item \emph{Medium level.}  A rewrite semantics steers between these two extremes.
  For example, Ariola \emph{et al}'s ``A call by need lambda calculus''\cite{ariola:call-by-need} shows how
  to give the semantics of a call-by-need language as a set of rewrite rules. The great
  advantage of this approach is that it is readily explicable to programmmers; indeed
  the execution of Haskell or ML programs is typically explained by successive rewrites
  of the program (e.g. inline this call, simplify this |case| expression, etc).
\end{itemize}
Up to this point there has been no satisfying rewrite semantics for functional logic langauges
(see \cref{sec:related} for previous work).
Our main contribution is to fill this gap with a rewrite semantics for \versecalc{}, that
has the following properties:
\begin{itemize}
\item The semantics is expressed as a set of rewrite rules.
\item Any rule can be applied, in either direction,
  anywhere in the program term (including under lambdas) to obtain an equivalent program.
\item The rules are oriented, with the intent that using them left-to-right makes progress.
\item Even given this orientation, the rules do not say in which rule should be
  applied where; that is the task of a separate \emph{evaluation stragegy}.
\item The rules can be applied by programmers, to reason about what their program does;
  and by compilers, to transform (and hopefully optimise) the program.
\item There is no ``magical rewriting'' (\cref{sec:magical}): all the variables on the
  right hand side of a rule are bound on the left.
\end{itemize}
The rewrite rules are given in Figures \ref{fig:rules1} and \ref{fig:rules2},
and are described next.

\subsection{Basic rewrites}

Looking at \cref{fig:general-axioms}, rules \rulename{p-add} and \rulename{p-gt}
should be familiar: they simply rewrite applications of |add| and |gt| to integer
constants.  For example $|applyx add (3,4)| \movesto |7|$.  The only unusual point is
that |gt| fails if $k_1 \leq k_2$ (rather than returning |False| as is more conventional),
and returns |k_1| otherwise.

% Rule \rulename{p-map} implements a map operation over arrays: It applies the function |f| to each value
% in turn, and collects the results into a array. If the function applications produce a choice
% of values, this will, as it should, produce a choice of arrays:
% \[
% |applyx map ((lam x (x choice  x+1)), (10,20))| \movesto^\ast |(10,20) choice (10,21) choice (11,20) choice (11,21)|
% \]

Sequencing, is very simple (rule \rulename{seq}):
|(e_1;e_2)|, simply reduces |e_1| to a value, and then discards it, returning
|e_2|.  The reason for evaluating |e_1| is for its unification effects.
Our insistence on clear sequencing also makes it possible to extend \versecalc{}
with more general effects, but that is beyond the scope of this paper.

\subsection{Function application} \label{sec:beta}

Beta-reduction is performed quite conventionally by \rulename{app-beta}; the
only unusual feature is that we use a |defKW| to bind |x| on the right-hand side,
and an equality |(x=v)| to bind |x| to the argument.
The rule may appear to use call-by-value, because the argument is a value |v|,
but remember that values include variables, and that variable may be bound to an
as-yet-unevaluated expression.  For example:
$$
|def y (y = 3+4; applyx (lam x (x+1)) y)|
\; \movesto \;
|def y (y = 3+4; def x (x=y; x+1))|
$$
Finally, the side condition $x \not\in \freevars{v}$ in \rulename{app-beta}
ensures that the |defKW x|
does not capture any variables free in |v|.  If |x| appears free in |v|, just use
\textalpha-conversion to rename |x| to $x' \not\in \freevars{v}$.

In \versecalc{}, arrays behave like (finite) functions, in which application is
indexing.  Rule \rulename{app-arr} describes how array application works.
Notice that \rulename{app-arr} does not require the argument to be an integer $k$; instead
the rule works by narrowing.  So the expression |def x ((2,3,2,7,9)(x) = 2; x)|
does not suspend awaiting a value for |x|; instead it explores all the
alternatives, returning |(0 choice 2)|.  This is a free design decision:
a suspending semantics would be equally easy to express.

\subsection{Unification: the easy bits}

Next we study unification, again in \cref{fig:general-axioms}.
Rules \rulename{ulit}, \rulename{ucon}, \rulename{ux1} and \rulename{ux2}
are the standard rules for unification. The only special thing
to note is that |(k_1 = k_2)| either fails if the values differ,
or yields common value if they are the same; and similarly for
tuples\footnote{An alternative choice would
for unification to yield |()| on success; but it does not make much difference
either way.}.  \rulename{ux1} and \rulename{ux2} make unfication fail if
you attempt to unify an integer with a tuple.
Slightly less obviously,
\rulename{ux3} through \rulename{ux6} make unification fail if you attempt to unify a
lambda or a built-in operation with any other value.  We discuss this design choice further in \cref{sec:unifying-lambda}.

\subsection{Unification: the \rulename{subst} rule}

Matters get more interesting when variables are involved.
The key rule is \rulename{subst}:
$$
\rulename{subst} \quad |X^[x==v]|  \movesto  |(subst X x v)^[x==v]|
        \quad \text{if $|x| \in \freevars{X}$, $|x| \notin \freevars{v}$} \\
$$
It says that if we have an equality |(x=v)| in a term,
we can replace ``nearby'' occurrences of |x| by |v|.  In this rule, |X| is an \emph{execution context},
defined in \cref{fig:syntax}.
In general, a ``context'' is a syntactic construct (in this case an expression)
with a single hole, written |hole|, in it.
The notation |X^[e]| is the expression obtained by filling the hole in |X| with |e|.
For example |(y = (hole, 4))| is a possible execution context, |X|; filling its hole with 99
gives the expression |(y = (99,4))|.
The notation |subst X x v| is the context obtained by replacing all free occurences of |x| in |X| by |v|.

So \rulename{subst} says that we can replace all occurrences of |x| by |v| in the
|X|-context surrounding an equality |(x=v)|, thereby propagating |x|'s value to those occurrence sites.
There are several things to notice:
\begin{itemize}
\item \rulename{subst} fires only when the right-hand side of the unification is a \emph{value} |v|, so that the substitution does not risk duplicating work, or choices. This
restriction is what implements so-called \emph{call-time choice} \cite{hanus:survey}.
We do not need a heap, or thunks, or updates; the equalities of the program elegantly
suffice to express the necessary sharing.
The fact that we substitute only values for variables also ensures that substitution is syntactically
valid; if we tried to substitute an expression |e| for a variable in |(x,2)| we would the
ill-formed expression |(e,2)|.
\item \rulename{subst}
  replaces the occurrences of |x| in |X|, \emph{but leaves the original |(x=v)| undisturbed}.
  For example, we can rewrite |((y=x+1; x=3); z=x+3)| to |((y=3+1; x=3); z=x+3)|, using
  |X = (y=x+1; hole)|.  We must not drop the |(x=v)| because there may be other occurrences of |x|
  ``further out'', such as |(z=x+3)| in this example.
\item If the equality |(x=v)| turns out to be the sole remaining occurence
      of |x| in the body of a |defKW|, then rule \rulename{def-elim} can drop both the |defKW|
    and the unification equation.
\item
Note carefully  that \emph{execution contexts |X| do not include |oneKW|, |allKW|, and choice}.
That restriction is the key to localising unification (\cref{sec:mixing}), and
the flexible/rigid distinction of
\cref{sec:rigid}. For example, consider the expression
|(y = ((x=3; x*2) choice (x=4)); (x+1,y))|.
We must not propagate the binding |(x=3)| to the expression |(x+1)|,
because the latter is outside the choice, and a different branch of the choice binds |x| to |4|.
But rule \rulename{subst}
\emph{can} propagate it locally
within the first arm of the choice, thus\footnote{
You may wonder if this local propagation is useful, a point we return
to in \cref{sec:local-prop}.}:
$$
|y = ((x=3; x*2) choice (x=4)); (x+1,y)|
\movesto
|y = ((x=3; 3*2) choice (x=4)); (x+1,y)|
$$
To make further progress, we need a rule for choice, \cref{sec:choice-rules}.
\item The $(x \in \freevars{X}))$ in \rulename{subst} prevents \rulename{subst} from
  begin able to fire infinitely often, doing nothing each time.  The other guard $(x \not\in \freevars{v})$
  also prevents \rulename{subst} from applying infinitely often, this time unrolling a recursive loop; but
  see \cref{sec:recursion}.
\end{itemize}


\subsection{Unification: recursion and the occurs check} \label{sec:occurs} \label{sec:recursion}

The classic ``occurs check'', rule \rulename{ux-occurs}, makes an equality like |(x=(x,3))| fail, because the only successful
unification would yield an infinitely-nested pair.
$$
    \rulename{ux-occurs} \quad |x=V^[x]| \quad \movesto \quad |fail| \quad \text{if }|V| \ne |hole|
$$
In this rule, |V| is an \emph{value context}, defined in \cref{fig:syntax}.
So \rulename{uc-occurs} says that the equality fails if there is a |V| such the equality looks like |(x=V^[x])|;
that is, if |x| occurs under a ``shell'' of tuples.  The guard $|V| \not= |box|$ is to avoid failure for |x=x|.

What if |x| occurs inside a lambda?  That is very useful, and we do not want to fail; for example
$$
|factorial = lam n (if (n=0) then 1 else n * applyx factorial (n-1))|
$$
\simon{Discussion on Slack.}

\subsection{Unification: administrative rules}

A number of rules are administative: they shuffle expressions about in order to make
the main unification rules apply.
Rule \rulename{def-float} moves a |defKW| ``out of the way''. For example,
the expression |(y = (def x (x,2)); dots)| does not bind |y| to a value, but if we float the |defKW| out
we get |def x (y=(x,2); dots)|, and now we may be able to make progress by substituting for |y|.
Similarly rules \rulename{unify-seql} and \rulename{unify-seqr} move sequencing out of unification,
again to make it more likely to get the form |(x=v)|.  Notice that |e_1|, |e_2| and |e_3| stay in the
same left-to-right order, there is no risk of re-ordering choices (c.f. \cref{sec:mixing}).

Rules \rulename{unify-unifyl} and \rulename{unify-unifyr} move a unification between values out of another unification.
Without these rules |(x=y)=1;y>0| would be stuck; but \rulename{unify-unifyl}
rewrites it to |((x=y);(y=1);y>0|, thus exposing |y=1| for further use by \rulename{subst}. Furthermore, in order
to prove confluence, we need to be able to freely move the equation |(v_1=v_2)|,
as discussed in \cref{sec:conf-move-eqn}. These rules could be more general, see \cref{sec:variations-liberate-unify}.

Finally, rule \rulename{swap} swaps the arguments to unification to make \rulename{subst} apply.

\subsection{Local substitution}

Consider this tricky term:
$$
|def x (x = (if (x=0; x>1) then 33 else 55))|
$$
What should this do? At first sight you might think it was stuck; how can we simplify the |if|
when its condition mentions |x| which is not yet defined.  But in fact rule \rulename{subst} allows
us to substitute \emph{locally} in the |X|-neighbourhood of the equality |(x=1)| thus:
$$
|def x (x = if (x=0; x>1) then 33 else 55)| \begin{array}[t]{l}
  \movesto |def x (x = if (x=0; 0>1) then 33 else 55)| \\
  \movesto |def x (x = if fail then 33 else 55)|\\
  \movesto |def x (x = 55)| \quad \movesto |55|
  \end{array}
$$
But this is example is arguably a weird corner case.  Perhaps we can simplify the system, by only allowing
substitution over the entire scope of the |defKW|, and combining it with \rulename{def-elim} thus:
$$
\rulename{global-subst} \quad |def x (X^[x==v])|  \movesto  |(subst X x v)^[v]|
        \quad \text{if $|x| \in \freevars{X}$, $|x| \notin \freevars{v}$} \\
$$
Now the tricky term is stuck; but maybe that does not matter. After
all, even with local substitution, the tricky term would be stuck if we
replaced |(x=0)| with |(x=33)|, as the reader may care to verify.
\emph{But the real reason we need local substitution is not expressiveness, but confluence.}
Suppose we use \rulename{global-subst} instead of \rulename{subst} and consider
$$
|def x (x = if (def y (y=x; y=0; y>1)) then 33 else 55)|
$$
In the condition of the |if| we have introduced a local variable |y|, and set it equal to |x|.
By using \rulename{global-subst} on |(y=x)|, we could recover the original tricky term, which is
stuck.

\emph{But by using \rulename{global-subst} on |(y=0)|, instead, we could simplify the |if|.}
Two different rewrites starting from the same term lead to non-joinable terms.
In effect, local substitution via \rulename{subst} has the same effect as introducing a local
alias for the unified variable.  This is a tricky point!

\subsection{Rules for choice} \label{sec:choice-rules}

The rules for choice are given in \cref{fig:choice}. Rules \rulename{fail-l} and \rulename{fail-r}
say that |fail| is the unit for choice |choice|.  Rules \rulename{one-value}, \rulename{one-choice}
and \rulename{one-fail} describe the semantics for |oneKW|, just as in \cref{sec:one}.
The \rulename{assoc-choice} is an administrative rule, to allow \rulename{one-choice} to fire.

The most interesting rule is \rulename{choose} which, just as described in \cref{sec:choice},
``floats the choice outwards'', duplicating the surrounding context.
But what ``surrounding context'' precisely? We use two new contexts, |SX| and |CX|, both
defined in \cref{fig:syntax}. A \emph{choice context} |CX| is like an
execution context |X|, \emph{but with no possible
  choices to the left of the hole}:
$$
CX ::= \hole \vb |CX == e| \vb |ce == CX| \vb |CX ; e| \vb |ce; CX|
\vb |def x CX|
$$
Here, |ce| is guaranteed-choice-free expression (syntax in \cref{fig:syntax}).
This syntactic condition is necessarily conservative; for example, a call |f(x)|
is considered not guaranteed-choice-free, because it depends on what function |f| does.
We must guarantee not to have choices to the left so that we preserve order --
see \cref{sec:mixing}.

The context |SX| (\cref{fig:syntax}) is a \emph{scope context}; it
ensures that |CX| is as large as possible.  This is a subtle point:
without this restriction we lose confluence.  To see this, consider\footnote{Remember, |if| is syntactic sugar for
  a use of |oneKW|, see \cref{sec:one}, but using |if| makes the example easier to understand.}:
$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\multicolumn{2}{l}{|def x (if (x>0) then 55 else 44; (x=1); (77 choice 99))|}\\
\movesto \{\rulename{subst}\} & |def x (if (1>0)  then 55 else 44; (x=1); (77 choice 99))|\\
\movesto \{\text{simplify |if|}\} & |def x (55; (x=1); (77 choice 99))|\\
\movesto \{\rulename{seq}\} & |def x ((x=1); (77 choice 99))|\\
\movesto \{\rulename{def-elim}\} & |1; (77 choice 99)|\\
\movesto \{\rulename{seq}\} & |77 choice 99|\\
\end{array}
$$
But suppose instead we floated the choice out, \emph{part-way}, like this:
$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\multicolumn{2}{l}{|def x (if (x>0) then 55 else 44; (x=1); (77 choice 99))|}\\
\movesto \{\text{Bogus \rulename{choose}}\} & |def x (if (x>0) then 55 else 44; ((x=1); 77) choice ((x=1); 99))|\\
\end{array}
$$
Now the |(x=1)| is inside the choice branches, so we cannot use \rulename{subst} to rewrite the
condition of the |if|.  Nor can we use \rulename{choose} again to float the choice further out,
because the |if| is not guaranteed choice-free (for example, the branches might contains choices).
So, alas, we are stuck!

Our not-entirely-satisfying solution is to force \rulename{choose} to float the choice all the way
to the innermost enclosing scope construct; hence the |SX| in the rule.

\subsection{\versecalc{} is lenient}

\versecalc{} is a \emph{lenient}, not lazy (call-by-need), nor strict (call-by-value).  Under lenient
evaluation, everything is eventually evaluated, but functions can run
before their arguments have a value.
Consider a function
call |applyx f e|.  In \versecalc{} applications are in administrative normal form (ANF),
so we must actually write |(x=e; applyx f x)|. This expression will not return a value until
|e| reduces to a value: that is, everything is eventually evaluated.  But even so |applyx f x| can proceed
to beta-reduce (\cref{sec:beta}), assuming we know the definition of |f|.
This is not just a way to get \emph{parallelism}, which was the motivation for introducing
lenience in the dataflow language Id \cite{lenience}; in a functional logic language
it is critical for \emph{semantics}.  Suppose |y = lam (p,q) (p=7;q)| and consider
$$
|def (f,y) (f = (lam p (x=7;p)); y = (if (x>0) then 7 else 8); applyx f y|
$$
Here |y| does not get a value until |x| is known; but |x| does not get its
value (in this case |7|) until |f| is called.  Without lenience this program would be stuck.


\section{Confluence}

The rules of our rewrite semantics can be applied anywhere, in any order, and they give meaning to programs without committing to a particular evaluation strategy. But then it better be the case that no matter how the rules are applied, one always obtains the same meaning for the program!

If the rewrite rules were terminating, then we would expect strong normalization: all possible execution paths lead to the same normal form. But since {\versecalc} has recursion, we can aim for \emph{confluence} instead: If $e_1 \movesto^\ast e_2$ and $e_1 \movesto^\ast e_3$, then we can find $e_4$ so that $e_2 \movesto^\ast e_4$ and $e_3 \movesto^\ast e_4$.

Confluence will give us the assurance that we will not get different results when choosing different rules, or get stuck with some rules and not with others.

\subsection{subst vs. subst}

The main source for possible non-confluence is rule \rulename{subst}: If we have multiple equations for a variable $x$ available, we can use any of them to rewrite. A typical example would be
\[ |def x (x=v_1; x=v_2; e)| \]
which we can rewrite by \rulename{subst} (and administrative \rulename{def-elim} and \rulename{seq}) to either
\[ |v_1=v_2; subst e x v_1| \quad \text{or} \quad |v_2=v_1; subst e x v_2|. \]
Can we still join these two expressions? The unification rules allow us to decompose an equality |v_1 = v_2| completely: Either it reduces to |fail|, which will swallow the whole expression, or to a sequence of equalities with a variable on (at least) one side. Using \rulename{subst} on these equations, we can join the occurrences of $v_1$ resp.\ $v_2$ in |subst e x v_1| resp.\ |subst e x v_2|.

So it seems that confluence is within reach? Unfortunately, not quite:

\subsection{Confluence up-to}

\begin{figure}
\[\begin{array}{lrcl}
    \rulename{def-swap} & |def (x,y) e| & \movesto & |def (y,x) e|\\
    \rulename{unify-move} & |X^[v_1=v_2]| & \movesto & |v_1=v_2;X^[v_2]| \\
    \rulename{var-swap} & |x=y| & \movesto & |y=x| \\
\end{array}\]
  \caption{Additional rewrite rules for confluence}
    \label{fig:rules-confluence}
\end{figure}

\label{sec:conf-move-eqn}

There some sources of non-confluence that we would consider insignificant. For example
| (def x (x=z));(def y (y=z)) |
can be reduced to
| (def (x,y) (x=z;y=z)) |
or
| (def (y,x) (x=z;y=z)) |, which are different expressions, but the difference is one we do not care about. We can capture this idea that our notion of confluence may ignore the order of |defKW|s by adding an additional rule, \rulename{def-swap} in \cref{fig:rules-confluence}, to the rewrite system. This is obviously looping, but this is not an issue.

Similarly, we do not care about where, within the same $X$-context, an equality is asserted, so we allow ourselves to move any such equation to the front of the $X$-context, using \rulename{unify-move}. We leave $v_2$ in place, just like \rulename{def-elim} does. Adding this rules does not allow more or fundamentally different evaluations; this motivated adding the rules \rulename{unify-unifyl} and \rulename{unify-unifyr}.

Finally, to make equality on values commutative, we add \rulename{var-swap}; else we’d get non-confluence from |def x (x=y;x=z)|, which can reduce to |y=z;z| or to |z=y;y|.

\subsection{Skew-confluence}

With with that out of the way, there still remains a source of non-confluence, due to recursion. In
\[ |def (x,y) (x=(1,y); y=(lam z x); x)| \]
we can apply \rulename{subst} to $x$ first and obtain the following reduction (omiting spelling out the application of rules \rulename{def-elim} and \rulename{seq}):
\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\movesto \{\rulename{subst}\}     & |def y (y=(lam z ((1,y))); (1,y))| \\
\movesto \{\rulename{subst-rec}\} & |def y (y=v_y; (1,y))| \quad \text{ where } |v_y| = |(lam z (def y (y = (lam z (1,y)); (1,y))))| \\
\movesto \{\rulename{subst}\}     & |(1,v_y)|  \\
\end{array}
\]
Alternatively, starting with |y = (lam z x)|, we obtain
\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\movesto \{\rulename{subst}\}     & |def x (x=(1,lam z x); x)| \\
\movesto \{\rulename{subst-rec}\} & |def x (x=v_x; x)| \quad \text{ where } |v_x| = |(1,lam z (def x (x = (1,(lam z x)); x)))| \\
\movesto \{\rulename{subst}\}     & |v_x|  \\
\end{array}
\]
Can we join |(1,v_y)| and |v_x|? Given $|v_x| \movesto^\ast |(1,lam z v_x)|$ and $|v_y| \movesto^\ast |lam z ((1, v_y))|$, we get
\[
\begin{array}{c@@{\,}c@@{\,}c@@{\,}c@@{\,}c@@{\,}c@@{\,}c@@{\,}c}
& |(1,v_y)| & \movesto^\ast & |(1,lam z ((1, v_y)))| & \movesto^\ast & |(1, lam z ((1, (lam z ((1, v_y))))))| & \movesto^\ast & \cdots \\
|v_x|     & \movesto^\ast & |(1,lam z v_x)| & \movesto^\ast & |(1, lam z ((1, (lam z v_x))))| & \movesto^\ast && \cdots
\end{array}
\]
and we \emph{cannot} join them; they keep “missing each other”.

But notice that as we keep evaluating these fixed-points, they produce the same “infinite expression” |(1, lam z ((1, (lam z dots))))| . This phenomenum has been studied before and led to a various generalizations of confluence to allow this behavior.

In particular the notion of \emph{skew-confluence} as introduced by \citet{ariola:skew-confluence}, applies here nicely: Slightly paraphrased it states that given $e_1 \movesto^\ast e_2$ and $e_1 \movesto^\ast e_3$, it suffices that for every \emph{finite} observation on expressions, both $e_2$ and $e_3$ eventually reduce to expression that are indistinguishable by that finite observation.

Until we have concluded the formal proof of skew-confluence, including the precise definition of finite observation, we state our aspiration as a conjecture:
\begin{conjecture}{Skew-confluence}
The reduction system $\mapsto$ is skew-confluent.
\end{conjecture}


\section{Related work} \label{sec:related}

\subsection{Flat vs higher order}.  When giving the semantics
of functional logic languages, a first-oder presentation is almost universal.
User-defined functions can be defined at top level only;
and function symbols (the names of such functions) are syntactically
distinguished from ordinary variables. As Hanus describes, it is possible
to translate a higher order program into a first-order
form\footnote{
  He does not mention this, but for a language with arbitrary nested lambdas
  one would need to do lambda-lifting as well, but that is a small point.}
using defunctionalisation \cite[Section 3.3]{hanus:survey}, and a buit-in
function |apply| function.
But this encoding is hardly a natural rendition of the lambda calculus, and it
obstructs the goal of using rewrite rules to explain to programmers how
their program might execute.

A strength of our presentation is that it deals natively with the full lambda calculus.

\subsection{Choice and non-determinism}

A significant difference between our presentation and earlier works is our
treatment of choice. Consider an expression like |(3 + (20 choice 30))|.
This is typically handled by a pair non-deterministic rewrite rules:
$$
|e_1 choice e_2| \movesto |e_1| \hspace{1cm} |e_1 choice e_2| \movesto |e_2|
$$
So our expression rewrites (non-deterministically) to either |(3+20)| or |(3+30)|;
and that in turn allows the addition to make progress.
Of course, including non-deterministic choice makes the rules are non-confluent by
construction.

In contrast, our rules never pick one side or the other of a choice.
And yet |(3 + (20 choice 30))| can make progress, by floating out the
choice (rule \rulename{choose} in \cref{fig:general-axioms}), thus
|(3+20) choice (3+30)|.  In effect, \emph{choices are laid out in space} (in
the syntax of the term), rather than being explored by
non-determinstic selection.  Rule \rulename{choose} is not a new idea -- indeed
it is common in calculi for calculi with choice (e.g. \cite{what}) --
but it does not appear to have been used to describe functional logic languages before.

\subsection{Treatment of logical variables} \label{sec:magical}

Our variables, introduced by |defKW|, are usually called \emph{logical variables},
or \emph{extra variables} in the literature.  The latter term arises because they
are typically introduced as variables that appear on the right-hand side of a function
defintion, but are not bound on the left.  For example, in Curry we can write
\begin{verbatim}
     f x | x =:= (a,b) = a where a,b free
\end{verbatim}
Here \verb!a! and \verb!b! are logical variables, not bound on the left; they
get their values through unificaiton.   In Curry they are explicitly introduced
by the ``\verb!where a,b free!'' clause, while in many other papers their
introduction is implicit in the top-level rules, simply by not being bound
on the left.  Logical variables are
at the heart of the ``logic'' part of functional logic programming.

To give a high-level semantics for non-strict, non-deterministic
functional logic languages, the brand leader is Constructor based
ReWrite logic (CRWL).
It is a ``big-step'' rewrite semantics,
one that rewrites a term to value in one big step.
\Citet{fraguas:rewriting} make a powerful case for
instead giving the semantics of a functional logic language using ``small-step'' rewrite
rules, more like those of the lambda calculus, that successively rewrite the term, one step at
a time, until it reaches a normal form.
they offer set of small-step rewrite rules, that is provably equivalent to
the CRWL framework.  Their key insight (inspired by 
\citet{ariola:call-by-need}'s formalisation of the call-by-need lambda calculus)
is to use |let| to make sharing explicit.

However both CRWL and Fraguas \emph{et al} suffer from a major problem:
they require something we call \emph{magical rewriting}. A key rewrite rule is this;
$$
\begin{array}{l}
f( \theta(e_1),\ldots, \theta(e_n) ) \movesto \theta( rhs ) \\
\text{if}
\begin{array}[t]{l}
  (e_1, \ldots, e_n) \movesto rhs
   \; \text{is a top-level function binding} \\
\text{and $\theta$ is a substitution mapping variables to closed values} \\
\text{and $dom(\theta) = \mathit{fvs}(e_1, \ldots, e_n, rhs)$}
\end{array}
\end{array}
$$
The substitution for the free variables of the left hand side can
readily be chosen by matching the left hand side against the call.
But the substitution for the extra variables must be chosen ``magically''
\cite[Section 7]{fraguas:rewriting} or clairvoyantly, so as to make the future execution
work out. This is admirably high level, because it hides everything
about unification, but it is not much help to a programmer trying to
understand a program, nor is it directly executable.

To explain actual execution, the state of the art is described by
\citet{hanus:semantics}.  They give both a big-step operational
semantics (in the syle of \citet{launchbury:natural}), and
a small-step operational semantics.  These two approaches both thread a
\emph{heap}, which holds
the unification variables and their unification state; and the small-step
semantics also has a \emph{stack}, to specify the focus of execution.
The trouble is that heaps and stacks are difficult to explain to a programmer,
and do not make it easy to reason about program equivalance.
To model residuation requires a new level of complexity, needing concurrency.

In contrast, our rewrite rules give a complete, executable (i.e. no ``magic'')
account of logical variables and choice, directly as small-step
rewrites on the original program, rather than as the evolution of a
(heap, control, stack) configuration. Moreover, we have no problem with
residuation.

\subsection{Intermediate language}

Hanus's \emph{Flat Language} \cite[Fig 1]{hanus:semantics} plays the same role as \versecalc{}:
it is a small core language
into which a larger surface language can be desugared.
There are some common features: variables, literals, constructor applications,
and sequencing (written \verb!hnf! in the Flat Langauge).
However, it seems that \versecalc{} has a greater economy of concepts.
In particular, the Flat Language
has two forms of equality \verb!(==)! and \verb!(=:=)!, and two forms
of case-expression, \verb!case! and \verb!fcase!.  In each pair, the former suspends
if it encounters a logical variable; the latter unifies or narrows
respectively. In contrast, \versecalc{}
has a single equality |(=)|, and the orthogonal |oneKW| construct, to deal with all four concepts.

The Flat Language has let-expressions \verb!(let x=e in b)!, where \versecalc{} uses
|defKW| and (again) unification.
The Flat Language also uses the same construct for a different purpose, to
bring a logical variable into scope, using the strange binding \verb!x=x!, thus \verb!(let x=x in e)!.
In contrast, |def x e| seems more direct.

\section{Variations and choices}

In a calculus like \versecalc{} there is room for many design variations.
We discuss some of them here.

\subsection{Unifying lambdas} \label{sec:unifying-lambda}

In \versecalc{} we say that any attempt to unify two lambdas (or primitive operations) fails -- even if the
lambdas are semantically identical.  The problem, obviously, is that it is hard
to tell if they \emph{are} semantically identical.

We cannot say that the attempt to unify gets stuck, because that leads to non-confluence.
Here is an expression that could rewrite in two different ways:
$$
\begin{array}{lll}
 \multicolumn{3}{l}{|def x (x = (lam p 1); x = (lam q 2); x ())|} \\
&    \movesto \{\textit{use \rulename{SUSBST} on second equality}\} & |(lam p 1) = (lam q 2); 1| \\
OR & \movesto \{\textit{use \rulename{SUSBST} on second equality}\} & |(lam q 2) = (lam p 1); 2|
\end{array}
$$
These two outcomes cannot be joined.  But making unification on lambdas fail, both outcomes
lead to |fail|, and confluence is restored.

\subsection{Choice and failure} \label{sec:choice-and-failure}

In \versecalc{} an expression delivers a \emph{sequence} of results, not a bag,
and certainly not a set (\cref{sec:choice}).  That suggests that a good evaluation strategy might be to
only explore the left branch of a choice first, and try the right branch only if former fails.  But consider
$$
|(if (x > 2) then e1 else e2); (x = 1 choice  fail)|
$$
The |if| is stuck until we have a value for |x|; we cannot float the choice out with \rulename{choose} because
|if| is no choice-free.  With the rules in \cref{fig:rules2} we \emph{can} use \rulename{fail-r} to rewrite
$|(x=1 choice fail)| \movesto |(x=1)|$; and now we can propagate the |(x=1)| to the |if| via \rulename{subst}
and make progress.  But to do this we must look at the right branch of the choice, before we know whether
the left branch will reach a value or fail.  There is nothing wrong with this, but it is arguably a bit peculiar that
|(x=1 choice e)| can substitute for |x| if and only if |e| fails.  Even |(x=1) choice (x=1)| cannot substitute
for |x|.

An alternative would be to drop \rulename{fail-l} and \rulename{fail-r}, and drop the |fail| terms only in
the rules for |oneKW| and |allKW|.  Both alternatives seems reasonable choices.

\subsection{Liberating more equations} \label{sec:variations-liberate-unify}

Rules \rulename{unify-unifyl} and \rulename{unify-unifyr} help to make more equations available for rewriting with \rulename{subst}. For example, |(x=y)=1;y>2| rewrites to |x=y;y=1;y>2|, which allows \rulename{subst} to rewrite with |y=1|, and the whole expression collapses to |fail|.

But the quite similar expression |(applyx f () =y)=1;y>2| is stuck, because \rulename{unify-unifyr} requires the inner unification between \emph{values}. We chose the more restrictive variant because confluence calls for just that, but one could have a more complete set of rules instead, covering all cases where two values ought to be equated:
\[\begin{array}{rcl@@{\hspace{10mm}}rcl}
|(v_1 = e) = v_2| & \movesto & |(v_1 = e); (v_1 = v_2)|
& |(e = v_1) = v_2| & \movesto & |(e = v_1); (v_1 = v_2)| \\
|v_1 = (e = v_2)| & \movesto & |(v_1 = v_2); (e = v_2)|
& |v_1 = (v_2 = e)| & \movesto & |(v_1 = v_2); (v_2 = e)| \\
 \end{array}\]

\joachim{Not sure if this section is worth it, or does a good job of explaining why we don’t use the full rules. Also these rules are not confluent.}

\subsection{Ordering and choices}

As we discussed in \cref{sec:choice-rules}, rule \rulename{choose} is less than satisfying, for two reasons.
First, the |CX| context uses a conservative, syntactic analysis for choice-free expressions; and second,
the |SX| context is needed to force |CX| to be maximal.  A rule like this would be more satisfying:
$$
\rulename{simpler-choose} \quad   |X^[ e_1 choice e_2 ]| \movesto |X^[e_1] choice X^[e_2]|
$$
The trouble with that is that it may change the order of the results (\cref{sec:mixing}).
Another possiblity would be to accept the the results may come out in the ``wrong'' order, but have
some kind of sorting mechanism to put them back into the ``right'' order.  Something like this:
$$
\rulename{labelled-choose} \quad   |X^[ e_1 choice e_2 ]| \movesto |X^[L; e_1] choice X^[R; e_2]|
$$
Here the two branches are labelled with |L| and |R|.  We can add new rules to reorder such
labelled expressions, something like
$$
\rulename{sort-l} \quad   |(R; e_1) choice (L; e_2)| \movesto |(L; e_2) choice (R; e_1)|
$$
We believe this can be made to work, but it adds unwelcome clutter to program terms, and the cure
may be worse than the disease.

